I've actually never really ran into with my 36 land rule. Jokes aside unless it's literally an omnath deck or meant for cedh that's my basic rule
Never put further thought into it, so maybe there are benefits I dont notice, but its served me well
I shoot for 37 or 38, normally. I think I have 40 in Kruphix and 44 in Windgrace
They do ~39 lands int he precons for a reason
I've just never really ran into a deck where I consistantly ran into a lack of land or an abundance. Least enough for me to notice
37 is pretty much always mine, but I'm also anti-mana rock in a lot of my less powerful decks (and I more or less always start a deck at a lower power level to see if I like it)
Mana rocks are my auto include. Obvious sol, relevant signets...  and go from there from what I have
I'm a creature of habit in building the skeleton of my deck
I shoot for 36. Some go up, some go down.
It's really more of the same thought of "play more of the deck's theme, even if it means playing it poorly"
How are you gonna know if you like a deck if every deck is just staples?
True. But the perks of the xonsistantcy in some of those staples are hard to ignore when they net you such great results :P
I like my silly decks, but I still need them to pace with others on some level
And I dont want to run into a situation where on turn 10 I draw a land with no cards in my hand >.> that's probably why I never go up
I'm sure someone can stats quote the reason on why adding 1-2 extra lands is statistically insignificant in the odds of drawing the land in that situation compared to if I stayed at 36... but eh
that's why you draw 2-3 cards every turn whenever possible so you never worry about getting land flooded
I guess my area just always has a bunch of new players. I'm constantly playing against precons or "please god help me build a deck" levels of power.
So it's easy to durdle and not worry about it to find out if I actually like the deck or not.
